Here's the registration in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Services
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `DataService` | **Singleton** | Holds an `HttpClient` and shared state (cache, auth tokens). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps state consistent app-wide. |
| `MainViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation to the page gets a fresh VM — no stale data, no cross-navigation state leaks. |
| `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Same reason — a new instance per visit so each detail screen starts clean. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Fresh UI state on each navigation. MAUI's Shell/navigation resolves them from DI automatically. |

**Key rule:** a transient service can depend on a singleton, but never register a singleton that depends on a transient (it would capture a stale transient forever). Here `DataService` has no VM/page dependencies, so the graph is safe.

If a ViewModel were expensive and you wanted to keep it alive across navigations, you could use `AddSingleton`, but that's the exception — transient is the safer default.
